{"type":"click","text":"C\n    \n      Config-Driven Engine + Escape Hatches\n      Declare workflows in JSON/YAML. Drop to code only when needed.\n      \n        How it works\n        \n          ENGINE (fixed, opinionated)\n          \n            Reads pipeline definitions → runs them\n            Built-in executors: claude, codex, shell, http\n            Built-in state machine, persistence, UI\n          \n          PIPELINE CONFIG (JSON)\n          \n            {\n              \"name\": \"research\",\n              \"stages\": [\n                { \"name\": \"gather\", \"executor\": \"claude\",\n                  \"prompt\": \"Research {{task.topic}}...\" },\n                { \"name\": \"analyze\", \"executor\": \"claude\",\n                  \"prompt\": \"Analyze: {{prev.output}}...\" },\n                { \"name\": \"report\", \"executor\": \"shell\",\n                  \"cmd\": \"pandoc -o report.pdf\" }\n              ],\n              \"on_complete\": { \"action\": \"webhook\", \"url\": \"...\" }\n            }\n          \n          ESCAPE HATCHES (when JSON isn't enough)\n          \n            Custom executor: \"executor\": \"./my-script.js\"\n            Stage hooks: \"before\": \"./validate.js\"\n            Custom state transitions: \"on_fail\": \"./decide.js\"\n          \n          \n            Git/PR management = a built-in \"action\" you reference in config.\n            \"on_complete\": { \"action\": \"git-pr\" } — zero code needed.\n          \n        \n      \n      \n        Pros\n          Lowest barrier to entry — just write JSON\n          UI can introspect pipeline definitions natively\n          Closest to what you already have (pipeline.json)\n          Escape hatches prevent hitting walls\n        \n        Cons\n          Config languages always grow — risk of \"YAML programming\"\n          Escape hatches can become the norm if config is too limited\n          Harder to type-check and debug than real code","choice":"c","id":null,"timestamp":1775455307606}
